{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"10467750-44e0-11ed-8bce-c55b627194d6","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rowsAreFullWidth":false,"backgroundImageUrl":"","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"d99150bf-5092-4d47-b757-0c5a0f108bc2","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Option Prices and the Risk-Free Rate","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"fe9ff98c-ce61-4648-bce1-c8025f844779"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"0e8fd67a-b01f-4c9c-b019-d7bc9d2784a0","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The value of a call option is increasing in the risk-free rate, but the value of a put option is decreasing in the risk-free rate. The intuition is that a higher discount rate reduces the present value of the strike price: Because you must pay the strike price to exercise a call option, reducing the present value of your payment increases the value of the option. However, because you ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"receive","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" the strike price when you exercise a put, reducing the present value decreases the value of the put option. We note, however, that given normal swings in the risk-free rate, they would be unlikely to change enough over the life of an option to have a substantial impact on the price of the optionâ€”that is, option values are not particularly sensitive to changes in the risk-free rate.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"8460fbbe-a48b-497f-a522-84708d1dc6c4"}]}]